.SH MakeMagGridPoint
Determine the three components of the magnetic field vector at a single
point.
.SH Usage
\f[CR]value\f[R] = MakeMagGridPoint (\f[CR]cilm\f[R], \f[CR]lmax\f[R],
\f[CR]a\f[R], \f[CR]r\f[R], \f[CR]lat\f[R], \f[CR]lon\f[R],
\f[CR]dealloc\f[R])
.SH Parameters
.TP
\f[CR]value\f[R] : output, real(dp), dimension (3)
Vector components (r, theta, phi) of the magnetic field at
(\f[CR]r\f[R], \f[CR]lat\f[R], \f[CR]lon\f[R]).
.TP
\f[CR]cilm\f[R] : input, real(dp), dimension (2, \f[CR]lmax\f[R]+1, \f[CR]lmax\f[R]+1)
The real Schmidt semi\-normalized spherical harmonic coefficients of the
magnetic potential.
The coefficients \f[CR]C1lm\f[R] and \f[CR]C2lm\f[R] refer to the cosine
(\f[CR]Clm\f[R]) and sine (\f[CR]Slm\f[R]) coefficients, respectively,
with \f[CR]Clm=cilm(1,l+1,m+1)\f[R] and \f[CR]Slm=cilm(2,l+1,m+1)\f[R].
.TP
\f[CR]lmax\f[R] : input, integer(int32)
The maximum spherical harmonic degree used in evaluating the function.
.TP
\f[CR]a\f[R]: input, real(dp)
The reference radius of the spherical harmonic coefficients.
.TP
\f[CR]r\f[R]: input, real(dp)
The radius to evaluate the magnetic field field.
.TP
\f[CR]lat\f[R] : input, real(dp)
The latitude of the point in degrees.
.TP
\f[CR]lon\f[R] : input, real(dp)
The longitude of the point in degrees.
.TP
\f[CR]dealloc\f[R] : input, optional, integer(int32), default = 0
0 (default) = Save variables used in the external Legendre function
calls.
(1) Deallocate this memory at the end of the funcion call.
.SH Description
\f[CR]MakeMagGridPoint\f[R] will compute the three components of the
magnetic field vector at a single point.
The input latitude and longitude are in degrees, and the output
components are in spherical coordinates (r, theta, phi).
The magnetic potential is given by
.PP
\f[CR]V = a Sum_{l=0}\(halmax (a/r)\(ha(l+1) Sum_{m=\-l}\(hal C_{lm} Y_{lm}\f[R],
.PP
and the vector magnetic field is
.PP
\f[CR]B = \- Grad V\f[R].
.PP
The coefficients are referenced to a radius \f[CR]a\f[R], and the output
values have the same units as the input spherical harmonic coefficients.
